{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"40ce679f-e30a-4849-9525-55b4be7c7723","content":"No worries — here's how to configure it. Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace with `\"command\": \"./path/to/MyMcpServer\"`.\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect it automatically. You can verify by opening the **MCP: List Servers** command from the Command Palette — your server and its tools should appear there.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f809c252-3470-44e9-a0dd-6dcacd9a757f","outputTokens":242,"requestId":"3848:147A9A:6CA4F37:750F54F:6A03CFE3"},"id":"d64e04ae-3b23-4a42-a1f0-b7d50637d951","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:12:10.339Z","parentId":"7242629d-c70a-4d44-b445-ed23b703117f"}
